<section xml:id="section-assignment1">
  <title>Assignment 1</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test the following series for convergence. (24)
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{1}{\pi^n} 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(n!)^2}{(3n+2)!} 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=2}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{n \ln n} 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=5}^\infty \frac{n^7 + 4n^2 + 3}{4n^8 - n^6 - 3n^3 + n}  
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \left(\sqrt{\pi} \right)^{\frac{n}{2}}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{\sin^2 n + \cos^2 3n}{n^2} 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{n^7+3n^6+n^2}} 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty  \frac{\ln n}{n + n^2\ln n}
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the Taylor series for each function around the given
        centre point <m>\alpha</m>, and determine the radius of
        convergence. (15)
        <ol>
          <li><md><mrow>
            \amp e^{x^3+1} \amp \amp  \alpha = 0 
          </mrow></md></li>
          <li><md><mrow>
            \amp \frac{1}{x} \amp \amp  \alpha = 4 
          </mrow></md></li>
          <li><md><mrow>
            \amp x^2 \ln x \amp \amp  \alpha = 4 
          </mrow></md></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Use the Lagrange error bounds to solve the following problems.
        (20)
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            Given <m>\ln (1-x)</m> as a Taylor series centered at
            <m>0</m>, if we want an approximation accurate to
            <m>\frac{1}{1000}</m> on <m>\left( \frac{-1}{2},
            \frac{1}{2} \right)</m>, what order of approximation is
            required?
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Given <m>e^{x^2}</m> as a Taylor series centered at
            <m>0</m>, what interval allows us to use the fifth order
            approximation with accuracy <m>\frac{1}{100}</m>. (You
            may need to guess the interval here. Guess to the nearest
            tenth.)
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Given the <m>0</m>th Bessel function on the interval
            <m>(-10,10)</m>, what accuracy is guaranteed by using a
            seventh order approximation? (Use the fact that the series
            is alternating to put a bound on the 8th derivative.)
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Approximate <m>e^4</m> to 3 decimal places  using a
            Taylor series.
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider two power series.
        <md><mrow>
          \amp \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n x^n \amp \amp 
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty b_n x^n 
        </mrow></md>
        If these two series have radii of convergence <m>R_1</m> and
        <m>R_2</m> respectively, give reasons why the sum and the
        product of the two series should have radius of convergence
        equal to the minimum of <m>R_1</m> and <m>R_2</m>. Give an
        example where the sum or product has a radius of convergence
        which is larger than both of the original radii. (6)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        We say that a series <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty</m> converges
        <em>uniformly</em> on <m>\RR</m> to a function <m>f(x)</m>
        if for all <m>\epsilon > 0</m>, there exists <m>N \in
        \NN</m> such that for all <m>x \in \RR</m> if <m>n \lt
        N</m> then <m> |f(x) - \sum_{k=0}^n c_n x^n | \lt
        \epsilon </m> Prove that the standard Taylor series for
        <m>e^x</m> centered at <m>0</m> does <em>not</em> converge
        uniformly. (Consider a lower bound on the error as <m>x</m>
        gets large). (6)
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
